02/05/2017 | News release | Distributed by Public on 02/05/2017 14:07
Limiting Liability and Insurance








[Attachment]


In our latest blog we look at whether the availability of insurance covering certain losses affects the validity of exclusion or limitation clauses that seek to exclude or limit liability for those losses.


        It is common for contracts to contain clauses whereby a party tries to exclude or limit its liability when something goes wrong. This can range from excluding all liability whatsoever, to excluding or limiting liability for certain types of losses- for example, indirect or consequential losses.
      

        Generally speaking, parties are free to include such clauses in their contracts, although liability for death or personal injury cannot be excluded. However, any such clause must satisfy the test of reasonableness contained in the Unfair Contract Terms Act 1977 (UCTA 1977)[1].
      

So what is reasonable?


        UCTA 1977 defines reasonableness as what is 'fair and reasonable' having regard to the circumstances known to the parties when the contract was made[2].
      

        This is not a particularly helpful definition, but luckily UCTA 1977 also provides guidelines for deciding what is reasonable[3]. These include the following factors:
      


          the relative bargaining positions of the parties; and
        

          whether a party knew or ought reasonably to have known of the existence and extent of the term.
        


        It will also be relevant to look at how the parties intended to allocate risk and whether the exclusion or limitation clause skews this.
      

Reasonableness and insurance


        Not surprisingly, the availability of insurance is a specific factor that the Courts take in account when deciding whether an exclusion or limitation clause is reasonable.
      

        For example, where a party purports to limit its liability to a specified amount, the Court will look at whether the party seeking to limit its liability to that amount has insurance to cover the liability, or could have had such insurance[4]. So where a party has indemnity insurance covering the liability well in excess of the amount it purports to limit its liability to, the limitation will probably be found to be unreasonable[5].
      

        On the flip-side, insurance will also be relevant where the other party (i.e. the party against whom the exclusion or limitation clause is being enforced) has, or could have had, insurance to cover its liability. So where the other party has insurance covering the type of loss, it is likely that the exclusion or limitation clause will be held to be reasonable. This is also the case where a party did not have such insurance, but could reasonably have obtained it if it had tried[6].
      

        By contrast, if the potential loss and damage was too wide and variable and could not be reasonably insured against, then a clause purporting to exclude or limit liability for that loss and damage is likely to be held unreasonable[7].
      

So is insurance relevant?


        The availability of insurance covering the type of loss or damage that a party seeks to exclude or limit is undoubtedly relevant. By way of summary, the availability of insurance covering that type of loss may well mean that the exclusion or limitation clause is found to be reasonable and therefore valid. Conversely, if the loss or damage is simply too wide to insure against, then the clause seeking to exclude or limit liability for that loss of damage will probably be found to be unreasonable and therefore invalid.
      

This blog was written by Will Cursham. For further information, please contact:


Will Cursham, associate, Construction


T: 0121 234 0066


E: [email protected] 


[1] Section 6(3).
      

[2] Section 11(1) UCTA 1977
      

[3] Schedule 2 UCTA 1977
      

[4] Section 11(4) UCTA 1977
      

[5] See for example, the case of The Trustees ofAmpleforth Abbey Trust v Turner and Townsend Project Management Limited [2012] EWHC 2137 (TCC), where the Court found that a clause purporting to limit the defendant's liability to £111,000 was unreasonable, in the light of the fact that it had professional indemnity insurance cover up to £10,000,000.
      

[6]Goodlife Food Limited v Hall Fire Protection Limited [2017] EWHC 767 (TCC).


[7] See, for example Balmoral Group Limited v Borealis (UK) Limited [2006] EWHC 1900 (Comm).














